    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						) Singularis est scientia,
    						qua[e] singularem efficit Operatorem.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				) Singular is the knowledge which produces a singular worker.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Specifica sunt arcana, qua[e] reddu[nt]
    						Experimentarium admirabilem.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				Specific are those mysteries, which restore the wonder of experience.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
    		
    		
    		<marginalia hand="Italian">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						Merus artiu[m], philosophia[e], professionu[m], arcanoru[m] pragmaticus: ca[e]teraru[m] literularu[m] securus.
    						Ha[e] faciunt vulgarem scholasticum: illa[e] rarum sapientem.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				The pragmatic man is undiluted by the arts, by philosopy, by the professions, by mysteries: he is untroubled by other letters.
    				The latter produce a common scholar: the former produces a rare sage.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
   
    		
    		<marginalia book_id="FolgersHa2" hand="Italian" id="Ha2.013v_0002" marginalia_continues_from="Ha2.014r_0002" marginalia_from_transcription="Ha2.014r.xml">
    			<language ident="LA">
    				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						[p. 347: Autotechni, et Cosmopragmatici Archignomicon.. Parcus uesc[e]ndi: parcissimus esto bibendi:
    						Parcior [e]t somni: parcior [a]t Veneris. Prodigus at soliai studij, techna[e]q[ue] profundia[e],
    						Pra[e]ualidiq[ue] actus, omnigeniq[ue] boni. Talis ego Parcus, talisq[ue] ego Prodigus omnes
    						Abijcio nugas: pragmata stricta premo. Quod potis est ars, aut virtus, aut = = da[e]dala praxis, Extentu Extentu proprio multiplicare decet. Huc arcana acma[e], stratagemataq[ue] eruta ab alto:]<!-- Continued from facing page, left margin, Ha2.014r -->
    						plus plusq[ue] ingenij: hic operum vlterius. Flexanima[e] Eutrapelus superaggerat
    					</marginalia_text>
    					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
    				</position>
    				<position book_orientation="270" place="intext">
    					<marginalia_text>
    						agmina Suad[a]e: Impressaq[ue] Fide, mirum operatur opus.
    					</marginalia_text>
    				</position>
    			</language>
    			<translation>
    				[p. 347: Chief piece of wisdom for the self-instructed and universally pragmatic man.. Live sparingly with eating and most sparingly with drinking:
    				moreover, be more sparing with sleep: but even more sparing with Love. However, be lavish alone in study, and in deep skill,
    				and superior behavior, and in every kind of good. Being so sparing and so lavish, I cast away all trifles: I pursue strictly practical
    				concerns. That which art can do, or virtue, or skilful action, to be extended on one's own, should be multiplied. For this purpose, 
    				the mysteries of perfection, and strategems drawn from on high:] more and more intellect: here more beyond works. Eutrapelus heaps over the movement of persuasive head-swaying: 
    				and with impressed faith, the wonderful work works.
    			</translation>
    		</marginalia>
        
